  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book \"Images of Immigrants and Refugees,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2019, demonstrates a significant scholarly uptake in discussions surrounding the portrayal of migrants, despite the absence of public discourse and citations in academic databases. It is positioned within a broader sustainable development agenda, aligning with at least one Sustainable Development Goal.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Images of Immigrants and Refugees\" has achieved a notable level of scholarly uptake, indicated by a strong citation count of 24. This suggests that the work resonates within academic circles, particularly in discussions related to immigration studies, cultural representation, and the societal dynamics surrounding refugees. This citation activity reflects the book's relevance in the scholarly landscape, likely serving as a critical resource for researchers and policymakers alike.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the book has not generated online mentions or public discourse through platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky, its academic insights remain crucial. It addresses complex issues surrounding the narratives and images associated with immigrants, potentially influencing both academic thought and policy frameworks, as indicated by its alignment with sustainability initiatives reflected in its association with at least one Sustainable Development Goal.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of reach, the work displays a commercial linkage, being available on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads, which enhances its accessibility to a broader audience. This commercial aspect might facilitate a wider conversation around the themes presented in the book, suggesting a potential for future discussions to emerge beyond direct academic citations.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's focus on images and narratives allows it to participate in ongoing dialogues related to cultural representations and their implications for society. While community discourse may not currently reflect engagement on social media or in public forums, the scholarly engagement with the text offers a foundation for future explorations and discussions related to immigration and refugee studies. Continued citations may also lead to a gradual increase in its visibility and impact within both academic and social spheres.</p>",
